thin the practice itself and come to be central to its ethos. The result is a sophisticated examination of musical survival and transformation that is also a meditation on temporality, labor, colonialism and nationalism, and the relationship of the living to the dead.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArabszAlgeriavMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aArabszMoroccovMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aMusiczAlgeriaxHistory and criticism. 0aMusiczMoroccoxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aandalusi music, urban, north africa, arabic, performance, tradition, medieval, islam, spain, national identity, postcolonialism, colonialism, empire, patrimony, embodiment, genealogy, heritage, secrecy, class, race, algiers, morocco, tlemcen, borderlands, nonfiction, history, anthropology, sociology, art, temporality, labor, nationalism, influence, ethnomusicology, andalusia, algeria, genre, revival.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019z97831106385160 cprintz978022632706840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226327372423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226327372/original  a978-3-11-063851-6  Urban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019c2016d2019  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles